          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Mass displacement in DRC</h2> 
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-23-1.png" alt="Mass displacement in DRC" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><strong>Summary: The UNHCR has labeled the DRC violence as the most alarming crisis, causing 230,000 to flee from the clashes.</strong></p>

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The violence in the eastern Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) has continued to escalate between non-state armed groups and the Congolese army in North and South Kivu provinces. Over 230,000 people have been displaced this year, per <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-01-2025-h1-1-reports-from-the-unhcr" target="_blank">reports from the UNHCR</a>. The eastern provinces are rich in resources but have been ravaged by conflict for three decades.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-01-2025-h1-2-m23-rebel-group" target="_blank">The M23 rebel group</a>, classified as a terrorist movement by the DRC government, continues to capture territory. The recent clashes in Masisi and the Lubero territories in North Kivu from 1-6 January have forced <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-01-2025-h1-3-150000-people-to-flee" target="_blank">150,000 people to flee</a>. Simultaneously, the local governments in South Kivu‚Äôs Fizi territory report that 84,000 people are now displaced.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Civilians face indiscriminate bombings, sexual violence, and deteriorating humanitarian conditions. Access to aid is severely hampered by security concerns, prompting urgent calls for international support. Many Congolese feel abandoned and overshadowed by other humanitarian crises, such as Sudan, Palestine, and Ukraine.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
