          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Russia offers to be a peacemaker</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><strong>Summary: Russia again offered to mediate the normalization of Armenia-Azerbaijan relations at a meeting in Moscow.</strong></p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
          Russian FM Sergey Lavrov met with Armenian FM Ararat Mirzoyan in Moscow, reiterating Russia‚Äôs <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-01-2025-h3-6-readiness-to-mediate" target="_blank">readiness to mediate</a> Armenia-Azerbaijan relations. Russia has made this offer multiple times since escalations between Armenia and Azerbaijan heated up in 2020 after decades of tensions over Nagorno-Karabakh. Mirzoyan hoped Russia would consider all aspects of recent events, "avoiding one-sided interpretations, which we have unfortunately seen recently."
</p>
<p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
          The meeting occurred during a strained period for Armenia-Russia ties. A traditional ally, Armenia has been seeking closer relations with the US and EU while accusing Moscow of favoring Azerbaijan in the Nagorno-Karabakh conflict and failing to prevent Azerbaijani advances. Russia criticized Armenia‚Äôs pro-Western shift. 
</p>
<p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
          Mirzoyan described the meeting as ‚Äú<a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-01-2025-h3-7-sincere-and-constructive" target="_blank">sincere and constructive</a>.‚ÄùHe also emphasized that Armenia‚Äôs economic ties with Russia, including its membership in the Moscow-backed Eurasian Economic Union (EAEU), remain key to their cooperation. ‚ÄúI hope that today‚Äôs discussion will serve to strengthen mutual understanding and continue further mutually beneficial cooperation,‚Äù Mirzoyan added.
</p>
        </mj-text>
