          <strong>üáπüá≠ Thailand: Authorities have denied any immediate plan to send 48 Uyghur refugees to China</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Thailand has denied accusations that they were going to immediately deport <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-01-2025-br1-8-48-uyghur-refugees" target="_blank">48 Uyghur refugees</a> to China amid warnings from UN experts and rights groups. The Uyghurs, who were detained since fleeing Xinjiang in 2013 and 2014, fear torture and abuse if returned. China has been repetitively accused of systematic human rights violations such as forced labor, mass detentions, and torture against Uyghurs, a predominantly Muslim minority in China.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">China denies these allegations of human rights abuses and any other wrongdoing. They counter that they are simply trying to combat extremism in Xinjiang. Thai officials say no deportation order exists despite reports suggesting preparations for repatriation. Rights groups and the UN are urging Thailand to prioritize the Uyghurs‚Äô safety and comply with human rights standards.</p>
