          <strong>üáªüá™ Venezuela: President urged migrants homecoming amid Trump‚Äôs firm stance on immigration</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">As Trump assumed office, things are up in the air for Venezuelan migrants and asylum seekers. Venezuelan President Nicolas Maduro urged migrants to return home, citing <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-01-2025-br2-9-respect-and-family-reunification" target="_blank">respect and family reunification</a> as key incentives. Maduro‚Äôs ‚ÄúReturn to the Homeland Plan,‚Äù launched in 2018, continues to charter flights for returning migrants, including from the US, after deportation flights resumed in 2023.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Maduro was recently sworn in for a disputed third term earlier this month. He faces a lot of international condemnation and US sanctions over alleged election fraud. Millions of Venezuelans have fled the country over political turmoil, economic collapse, and resource shortages. Trump‚Äôs presidency further complicates things for Venezuelans as they have to reckon with potential deportation and fear retribution back home.</p>
        </mj-text>
