          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What is an executive order?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-23-3.png" alt="What is an executive order?" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">An executive order is a <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-01-2025-f1-10-formal-directive" target="_blank">formal directive</a> issued by the President of the United States to manage the federal government's operations. Like federal regulations, executive orders are numbered consecutively and have the force of law, but they do not require congressional approval. Executive orders, proclamations, and administrative orders are published in the Federal Register.</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Executive orders must be based on constitutional or statutory authority and often specify how federal agencies should implement laws passed by Congress. They are subject to judicial review and can be overturned if found unconstitutional. Authority for issuing the orders is rooted in <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-01-2025-f1-11-article-ii-of-the-us-constitution" target="_blank">Article II of the US Constitution</a>, which states: "The executive power shall be vested in a president of the United States of America."</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Throughout American history, presidents have used executive orders for <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-01-2025-f1-12-various-purposes" target="_blank">various purposes</a>. Notable examples include Lincoln's Emancipation Proclamation and Franklin D. Roosevelt's establishment of Japanese-American internment camps during World War II. However, some critics see executive orders as ineffective, particularly in recent administrations, because one president can easily undo the orders of their predecessor, rendering them potentially counterproductive.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
